<h2>Who Uses an Online Pay Stub Generator</h2>

<h3>Gig workers and contractors (the largest group)</h3>
<p>DoorDash, Uber, Lyft, Instacart, Fiverr, Upwork, TaskRabbit, and other platforms classify workers as independent contractors. No pay stubs are issued. An online generator fills this gap for apartment applications, personal loans, and other income verification needs.</p>

<h3>Small businesses issuing stubs to employees</h3>
<p>Small employers without payroll software can use this online tool to generate pay stubs for employees each pay period. Many states legally require pay stubs with each paycheck. This tool handles the calculations and produces a professional document you can email or print.</p>

<h3>Self-employed professionals</h3>
<p>Freelancers, consultants, and sole proprietors who invoice clients directly have no employer generating pay stubs. Online pay stub generators convert invoice-based income into the standardized format that rental applications and lenders require.</p>

<h2>Online vs. Downloaded Template: Key Difference</h2>
<p>An online generator calculates taxes for you. A downloaded Word or Excel template gives you blank fields to fill in -- including the tax fields -- which means you have to calculate every number yourself or leave them wrong. Tax calculation errors on a manually completed template are a common reason self-generated stubs get rejected by reviewers who notice the numbers do not add up.</p>

<p>This online generator handles all the math automatically using current tax tables. You enter gross pay and basic information; the tool produces accurate deduction amounts without you needing to know any tax math.</p>

<h2>How to Enter Each Field Online</h2>

<p><strong>Employer name:</strong> The legal name of whoever pays you. For DoorDash drivers: "DoorDash, Inc." For Uber: "Uber Technologies, Inc." For self-employed: your business name or your name plus "Self-Employed."</p>

<p><strong>Employee name:</strong> Your legal name as it appears on ID and tax documents.</p>

<p><strong>Pay period:</strong> Weekly, biweekly, semi-monthly, or monthly. Choose the frequency that matches how often you actually receive income from this source.</p>

<p><strong>Gross pay:</strong> Your total earnings for the pay period before any deductions. For gig workers: the total deposited by the platform for that week. For contractors: the invoice total received. For hourly workers: rate × hours.</p>

<p><strong>Filing status:</strong> How you file your taxes -- Single, Married Filing Jointly, Married Filing Separately, or Head of Household.</p>

<p><strong>State:</strong> Where you work (or primarily receive income). Determines state income tax rate.</p>

